aws.com%2F4e%2F07%2F197fd3e246b589deedd57268faf6%2F202506220-npr-biosphere00056.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5107x2873+0+265/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4e%2F07%2F197fd3e246b589deedd57268faf6%2F202506220-npr-biosphere00056.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5107x2873+0+265/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4e%2F07%2F197fd3e246b589deedd57268faf6%2F202506220-npr-biosphere00056.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5107x2873+0+265/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4e%2F07%2F197fd3e246b589deedd57268faf6%2F202506220-npr-biosphere00056.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5107x2873+0+265/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4e%2F07%2F197fd3e246b589deedd57268faf6%2F202506220-npr-biosphere00056.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5107x2873+0+265/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4e%2F07%2F197fd3e246b589deedd57268faf6%2F202506220-npr-biosphere00056.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5107x2873+0+265/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4e%2F07%2F197fd3e246b589deedd57268faf6%2F202506220-npr-biosphere00056.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5107x2873+0+265/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4e%2F07%2F197fd3e246b589deedd57268faf6%2F202506220-npr-biosphere00056.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5107x2873+0+265/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4e%2F07%2F197fd3e246b589deedd57268faf6%2F202506220-npr-biosphere00056.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5107x2873+0+265/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4e%2F07%2F197fd3e246b589deedd57268faf6%2F202506220-npr-biosphere00056.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5107x2873+0+265/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4e%2F07%2F197fd3e246b589deedd57268faf6%2F202506220-npr-biosphere00056.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5107x2873+0+265/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4e%2F07%2F197fd3e246b589deedd57268faf6%2F202506220-npr-biosphere00056.jpg" class="img" alt="Trees grow against the windows at Biosphere 2 on June 20, 2025 in Oracle, Ariz., U.S." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Trees grow against the windows at Biosphere 2 on June 20, 2025 in Oracle, Ariz., U.S.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Caitlin O'Hara/for NPR                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Biosphere 2 is a living laboratory established in the late 1980s and early 1990s to explore whether humans could survive in an artificial, self-sustaining ecosystem. Inside, you'll find a humid, decades-old rainforest filled with a rich variety of plant life. There is also a miniature manmade ocean, as well as a mangrove wetland and a fog desert landscape. The structure rises to 91 feet at its highest point, covers more than three acres, and features 6,500 windows. Today, the University of Arizona operates the project with a different mission. Scientists are conducting research aimed at helping us adapt to Biosphere 1 — our Earth — and the climate change we are causing. Take a &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/07/07/nx-s1-5442529/biosphere-2-earth-sciences-climate-change" target="_blank"&gt;look at some of the experiments&lt;/a&gt; Biosphere 2's scientists have dreamt up in the large glass building.&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;3 things to know before you go&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-76544" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 3634;         --source-height: 2044;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3634x2044+0+283/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0f%2F3a%2Fdf046f004350be4b9171fc75d520%2Fgettyimages-470828983.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3634x2044+0+283/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0f%2F3a%2Fdf046f004350be4b9171fc75d520%2Fgettyimages-470828983.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3634x2044+0+283/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F0f%2F3a%2Fdf046f004350be4b9171fc75d520%2Fgettyimages-470828983.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3634x2